        heroTitle: "Taxi Toulouse → Mazamet",
        heroSubtitle: "Your Toulouse → Mazamet transfer at €115 — €150. 95 km via the A68 and D612.",
        description: "Mazamet, a wool-processing town at the foot of the Montagne Noire, is 1h10 from Toulouse via the A68 then D612 through Castres.",
        routeDescription: "The route takes the A68 to the Castres junction, then the D612 through the Tarn to Mazamet at the foot of the Montagne Noire.",
        introduction: "Mazamet is a town with a singular destiny, shaped by the wool-pulling industry — the art of separating wool from sheepskin. In the 19th century, this small Tarn town became the world's leading wool-pulling centre, importing skins from Australia, South Africa and Argentina to feed its factories along the Arnette river. The great Mazamet families (Cormouls-Houles, Olombel, Tournier) built sumptuous bourgeois mansions that give the town an unexpectedly prosperous air. But Mazamet's jewel is Hautpoul, a medieval village perched on a rocky spur overlooking the Arnette valley. Accessible via the spectacular Himalayan footbridge (140 m long, 70 m above the void), Hautpoul is a Cathar site destroyed in 1212 during the crusade. Now restored, the village hosts artisan workshops and a medieval festival. The Montagne Noire, peaking at Pic de Nore (1,211 m), offers beech and fir forests, hiking trails and welcome coolness in summer. Mazamet is also the gateway to the Haut-Languedoc Regional Natural Park, a wild territory between the Tarn and Herault departments.",
        itineraire: "From Toulouse, your driver takes the eastern ring road then the A68 motorway towards Albi. At the Castres interchange (exit 5), you leave the A68 for the D612 dual carriageway towards Castres and Mazamet. You first cross the Tarn plain with its cereal crops, then the landscape becomes undulating as you enter the Sor valley, a tributary of the Agout. Castres appears with its picturesque houses on the Agout. You cross the town then continue on the D612 towards Mazamet. The landscape changes dramatically: the first foothills of the Montagne Noire rise up, oak forests give way to beech and fir. Mazamet nestles in the Arnette valley, overlooked by the Hautpoul spur. Tolls are limited to the A68 section (approximately €4). The journey takes 1h10 under normal conditions. Crossing Castres can add 10-15 min during rush hours.",
        conseils: "In Mazamet, the Hautpoul visit is essential. The Himalayan footbridge (paid entry, approximately €5) offers thrills and a vertiginous view over the valley. The restored medieval village takes 1h to explore with its artisan workshops (pottery, forge, stained glass). The Maison du Bois et du Jouet, an interactive museum, delights children. To understand the wool-pulling history, the museum of Catharism and wool-pulling traces this unique industrial saga. Foodies will enjoy mountain charcuterie (black pudding, dry sausage) and sheep's cheese from Montagne Noire farmers. In summer, the Montagne Noire's coolness (10C less than Toulouse) is a welcome refuge. Pic de Nore trails offer magnificent hikes with views over the Pyrenees and Mediterranean on clear days. The Hautpoul medieval festival (July) brings the village alive with tournaments, banquets and fire shows.",
        comparaisonTransport: "The Lio bus Toulouse — Mazamet costs €2 but takes about 2h with a connection in Castres. There is no direct train. By car, expect €10 in fuel and €4 in tolls. The TaxiNeo taxi at €115 — €150 is the most practical solution for a direct transfer. Ideal for hikers heading to the Montagne Noire, families visiting Hautpoul and its footbridge, or travellers in transit to the Haut-Languedoc. For 3-4 passengers, the per-person cost (€29-50) is reasonable for a route with no direct public transport.",
