        introduction: "Millau is a town at the gateway to grandiose landscapes, world-famous for the Millau Viaduct, the tallest bridge in the world (343 m, taller than the Eiffel Tower). Designed by architect Norman Foster and engineer Michel Virlogeux, this engineering masterpiece inaugurated in 2004 spans the Tarn valley with dizzying elegance. But Millau existed long before the viaduct: the town has been a glove-making centre since the 12th century, with a tradition of exceptionally fine lambskin leather (Millau gloves adorned the hands of European courts). The Millau Museum traces this history. The town is also the gateway to the Tarn Gorges, a spectacular 50 km canyon between 500 m cliffs, navigable by canoe-kayak. To the south, the Roquefort caves (12 km) house the ageing of the 'king of cheeses', Roquefort AOC, in the natural scree of the Combalou. The Grands Causses (Larzac, Sauveterre, Noir, Mejean) frame Millau with their immense limestone plateaux, a paradise for hikers, paragliders and lovers of wide-open spaces. The gastronomy is Aveyronnaise: aligot, tripous, Roquefort, flaune, rye bread.",
